    h4.govuk-heading-m Check the applicant is not a company, charity or not for profit organisation
    P Help with fees is generally only available to individuals; the scheme does not apply to other types of business, companies or charities.
    h4.govuk-heading-m There are some exceptions:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li sole traders; this is someone trading as an individual

    p Outside Help with Fees companies applying to the Gambling Appeals Tribunal can apply for fee remission using separate forms and guidance.
    p In other areas, those not able to apply for Help with Fees could apply for an exceptional fee remission under the Lord Chancellor’s Exceptional Power. See Section 7 on the #{link_to 'staff guide', 'https://intranet.justice.gov.uk/about-hmcts/my-work/help-with-fees/staff-guidance/', target: '_blank'}


    h4.govuk-heading-m#check-applicant-is-not Check the applicant is not one of the following:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li on the list of #{link_to 'vexatious litigants', 'http://www.gov.uk/guidance/vexatious-litigants', target: '_blank'} banned from starting court proceedings without permission

      li bound by a #{link_to 'general civil restraint order (CRO)', 'http://www.gov.uk/guidance/general-civil-restraint-orders-in-force', target: '_blank'} to stop them from bringing certain cases to court
      li bound by an #{link_to 'extended civil restraint order (CRO)', 'http://www.gov.uk/guidance/extended-civil-restraint-orders-in-force', target: '_blank'} to stop them making applications in certain courts or make further court claims
      li someone other than the person who must pay the fee; third parties may not apply for help with fees unless they're acting as a litigation friend, parent or guardian. If they are, they declare the applicant’s financial details but they provide their own contact details and signature.

    h4.govuk-heading-m#check-the-fee Check the fee:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li was not processed through the money claim online (MCOL)
      li is not for a search or request for duplicate documents (unless the applicant did not receive the originals or had no fixed address when an order was made)
    h4.govuk-heading-m id="not-eligible" If the applicant is not eligible to apply
    p If the applicant is not eligible to apply for any of the reasons above, return their application with a letter to say why it cannot be accepted.
    h4.govuk-heading-m The most common reasons applications can’t be processed:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li statement of truth must be signed
      li the application form is incomplete
      li the applicant is receiving legal aid
      li the applicant is a vexatious litigant or bound by an order that means they’re not eligible to apply
      li the applicant wants help with a fee processed through the money claim online (MCOL) services
      li the applicant wants help with a fee for a search or request for duplicate documents

    p If the applicant can correct the error, please make this clear.

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="online-applications" Online applications
    p The help with fees online service asks similar questions to the form EX160. Applicants only answer questions relevant to their situation so they may find it quicker and easier than using the paper form.
    p You can process online applications in a similar way to paper applications for help with fees.
    ol.govuk-list.govuk-list--number
      li Everyone who applies for help with fees online will get a reference number, like this: HWF-A73-L8T
      li You’ll find the reference number on the court or tribunal form in the HWF reference number field, or in a letter if the applicant is applying for a refund
      li Enter this reference number in the ‘Process an online application field’
      li Check the name of the applicant is correct and enter the following details: fee; jurisdiction; and form name or number. You can also select whether it’s an emergency case
      li Check all the details you’ve entered are correct on the ‘Check details page’ and click ‘Complete processing’
      li You’ll see the outcome of the application together with the reference number on the final page. Enter the application reference number into the case management system as usual

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="outside-uk" People applying from outside the UK
    p You can accept applications from people living outside the UK if their case is being dealt with by a court or tribunal in the UK. The only exception is those outside the UK bringing an appeal in the First-tier Tribunal (Immigration & Asylum Chamber).

    p You can still accept an application from someone who has ‘no recourse to public funds’ specified on their visa. They will be assessed in the same way as any other foreign national or non-resident UK citizen.

    p Make sure the application uses UK pounds sterling for details of income.

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="multiple-claimants" Multiple claimants
    p If you're processing an application where there are multiple claimants, first check whether all of them are eligible.
    p If all claimants are eligible for help with the fee, you should only leave one processed application in the system and delete the other applications. This is important so that the fee isn't counted more than once.
    p If not all claimants are eligible, then the fee will still need to be paid. In some cases the amount to be paid will be reduced if 2 or more claimants are eligible. Please check the #{link_to 'policy guidance on the intranet', 'https://intranet.justice.gov.uk/about-hmcts/my-work/help-with-fees/staff-guidance/', target: '_blank', title: 'links to PDF document'} for more details.


    h3.govuk-heading-l id="ni-number" National Insurance number
    h4.govuk-heading-m If NI number isn't provided:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li check answer to question 9
      li if 'No', continue to process without NI number
      li if 'Yes', don't process and contact applicant by phone to ask for their NI number
    p If you're unable to contact the applicant by phone, you should return the application and ask them to provide their National Insurance number, a letter confirming that they're receiving benefits or to apply on the basis of their income.

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="ho-number" Home Office reference number
    p To allow those under immigration control who don’t have a National Insurance number to apply online on the basis of their income, we are now asking for a Home Office reference number instead. This is not compulsory on the paper form, but you should enter it here if the application provides one.

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="status" Status
    p There are some exceptions to the standard definition of 'single' for someone without a partner who relies on their own income, for example when the case involves:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li divorce, dissolution or annulment*
      li gender recognition applications
      li domestic violence
      li forced marriage
      li where a couple are both part of a 'multiple fee' group
    p * If an applicant is involved in a divorce, dissolution or annulment case they should be considered to be part of a couple if they've formed a new relationship where they're living together and sharing a joint income.

    p
    h4.govuk-heading-m Married or living with someone and sharing an income
    p Applicants should still be considered to be married or living with someone and relying on their joint income for household expenses. For example if one or both are:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li serving in the armed forces
      li are in prison
      li living in residential care

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="refunds" Refunds
    h4.govuk-heading-m Check the refund:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li is for a fee paid less than 3 months ago
      li hasn't already been refunded
    p If the fee was paid more than 3 months ago, your delivery manager may be able to extend the period of 3 months if they think there's good reason to do so.

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="emergency" Emergency cases
    p An emergency case is one where delay may harm the applicant or the applicant’s case.
    h4.govuk-heading-m Example of emergency cases:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li suspending an eviction
      li insolvency applications
      li children or vulnerable adults
      li injunctions
      li ‘out of hours’ provisions at the Royal Courts of Justice

    p In some situations there's no time for the applicant to complete a help with fees form before their emergency case is heard.
    p The delivery manager can ask the applicant (or their legal representative) for an 'undertaking' to apply for help with fees or pay the fee within 7 days.
    p Applicants providing an undertaking must complete #{link_to 'form EX160B', 'http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetLeaflet.do?court_leaflets_id=2834', target: '_blank'}

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="savings" Savings and investments

    h4.govuk-heading-m When applicant (or their partner) are 66 or over
    p They may have up to £16,000 in savings and investments.

    h4.govuk-heading-m When applicant (and their partner) are under 66
