    h3.govuk-heading-l id="benefits" Benefits
    p If an applicant is applying for help with fees based on receiving benefits, you’ll receive confirmation from the Department for Work and Pensions that they’re receiving one of these 5 benefits:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li
        | income-based Jobseeker's Allowance
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(JSA)
      li
        | income-related Employment and Support Allowance
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(ESA)
      li
        | Income Support
      li
        | Universal Credit
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(and they’re earning less than £6,000 a year before tax and National Insurance)
      li
        | Pension Credit
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(guarantee credit)

    h4.govuk-heading-m id="benefits-unexpected" If you get an unexpected benefits result
    p It takes a couple of days for the Department for Work and Pensions to be updated with information about new applicants.
    p If you’re processing the application at the counter, ask the applicant for an official letter to show they’re receiving these benefits.

    h4.govuk-heading-m Check the name of the benefit
    p There are some benefits that are similarly named to the 5 benefits that qualify an applicant for help with their fee. If an applicant is receiving one of the benefits listed below, they are NOT automatically eligible. Instead they should apply on the basis of their income.
    h4.govuk-heading-m They are:
    ul.govuk-list.govuk-list--bullet
      li
        | contribution-based Job Seekers Allowance
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(JSA)
      li
        | contribution-based Employment and Support Allowance
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(ESA)
      li
        | Pension Credit (savings credit)
      li
        | Universal Credit
        span.hint
          | &nbsp;(and they’re earning more than £6,000 a year before tax and National Insurance)

    h4.govuk-heading-m If the applicant receives joint benefits
    p If the benefit is in the applicant's partner's name you'll need to see evidence of this. If you're processing the application at the counter, ask for an official letter to show they’re receiving a joint benefit as well as a letter to show they live at the same address as their partner.

    h4.govuk-heading-m Accepting benefits letters
    p You can accept a letter provided by the applicant to show they’re receiving benefits, even when the online benefits check result is negative. This may be necessary when the applicant is receiving a joint benefit for example.

    h4.govuk-heading-m Children
    p Appellants are asked how many children they (and their partner) are financially responsible for. This is now split into two questions on the form – those that live with them, and those that do not but are financially supported by them.

    p The children need to be under 16 or between 16-19, single, living at home and in full-time education (not including studying for a degree or other higher education qualification).

    p Add those two numbers together and enter it on the application.

    h3.govuk-heading-l id="income" Total monthly income
